description:
## Purpose

Initialize the anvil project repository and create the CLI entry point. anvil is a Bun + TypeScript CLI tool that scaffolds software projects (Go, TypeScript/JS, Python) with anti-slop lint rules, quality tooling, git hooks, seed code, and agent instructions.

This deliverable creates the foundation that every other deliverable builds on: the package.json with all dependencies, TypeScript config, source directory structure, and the Commander.js CLI that parses commands.

## Spec References

- specs/cli/scaffold-engine.md — Architecture > Component Overview (src/ layout)
- specs/cli/scaffold-engine.md — Design Decisions table (Commander.js, @inquirer/prompts, EJS, Chalk, Bun built-ins)
- specs/PROJECT.md — Constraints table (Bun + TypeScript runtime)

## Files to Create

```
anvil/
├── package.json          # Bun project with all dependencies
├── tsconfig.json         # Strict TypeScript config
├── src/
│   ├── cli.ts            # Commander program definition
│   ├── types.ts          # Shared types (D-44) — see Canonical Type Definitions below
│   ├── commands/
│   │   ├── init.ts       # Stub (exports empty async function)
│   │   └── doctor.ts     # Stub
│   ├── scaffold/         # Empty directory (populated by later tickets)
│   └── generators/       # Empty directory
└── bin/
    └── anvil.ts          # Executable entry: imports and runs cli.ts
```

`anvil update` is deferred to v2 (D-39). Do NOT create `src/commands/update.ts`.

## Required Behavior

1. `package.json` must include:
   - name: "anvil"
   - type: "module"
   - bin: { "anvil": "./bin/anvil.ts" }
   - dependencies: `commander`, `chalk`, `@inquirer/prompts`, `ejs`, `diff`, `write-file-atomic`, `picomatch`, `pino`, `zod` (per D-67 Part B)
   - devDependencies: `@types/bun`, `@types/ejs`, `typescript`, `vitest`, `yaml`, `node-pty` (yaml + node-pty per D-67 Part B; node-pty is a dev-only sandbox-harness dep)
   - scripts: { build, test, lint, format }
   - Note: vendored libs (`proper-lockfile`, `dir-compare`) are NOT in package.json — they live in `src/internal/` (D-67 Part C; see TIX-000066/067/068).

2. `src/cli.ts` must:
   - Create a Commander program named "anvil"
   - Register `init` command with `--lang <language>` required option (choices: golang, typescript, python)
   - Register `--non-interactive` flag on `init` (CLI-05; D-67 — opt-in only, not auto-detected)
   - Register `--dry-run` flag on `init` (CLI-06)
   - Register `doctor` command
   - Register `--version` as a top-level flag from package.json version field (CLI-07; no subcommand)
   - The CLI registers `init` and `doctor` only. `anvil update` is deferred to v2 (D-39).
   - Export the program for testing
   - Each command calls its stub handler from `src/commands/`

3. `bin/anvil.ts` must:
   - Import the program from `src/cli.ts`
   - Call `program.parse(process.argv)`
   - Have a shebang line: `#!/usr/bin/env bun`

4. Command stubs in `src/commands/` must:
   - Export a default async function that accepts parsed options
   - Log "not yet implemented" with chalk and exit cleanly

5. `tsconfig.json` must use strict mode, ES2022 target, NodeNext module resolution

## Tests Required

- `src/cli.test.ts`:
  - Parsing `anvil init --lang typescript` extracts lang option correctly
  - Parsing `anvil init --lang golang` works
  - Parsing `anvil init --lang python` works
  - Parsing `anvil init --lang rust` fails (invalid choice)
  - Parsing `anvil init --lang typescript --non-interactive` sets the flag (CLI-05; D-67)
  - Parsing `anvil init --lang typescript --dry-run` sets the flag (CLI-06)
  - Parsing `anvil --version` outputs the version from package.json (CLI-07)
  - Parsing `anvil update` (any form) fails with an unknown-command error (D-39 — deferred to v2)

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `bun install` succeeds with zero errors
- [ ] `bun run src/cli.ts init --lang typescript` prints "not yet implemented" and exits 0
- [ ] `bun run src/cli.ts --version` prints the version from package.json
- [ ] `bun run src/cli.ts --help` shows `init` and `doctor` (not `update`)
- [ ] `bun run src/cli.ts update` exits non-zero with an unknown-command error
- [ ] `bun test` passes all CLI parsing tests
- [ ] TypeScript compiles with zero errors (`bunx tsc --noEmit`)

## Out of Scope

- Actual init/doctor logic (later tickets)
- `anvil update` (deferred to v2 per D-39)
- Template files or static assets
- EJS template rendering
- Any scaffold output generation

## Canonical Type Definitions (D-44)

This deliverable owns `src/types.ts` — the single source of truth for cross-module types. Every downstream module imports from this file rather than redefining shapes inline. Copy the definitions below verbatim.

```typescript
// ─── Scaffold context ────────────────────────────────────────────────
export type Lang = 'typescript' | 'golang' | 'python';
export type PackageManager = 'bun' | 'npm' | 'pnpm' | 'yarn';

export interface ToolchainVersions {
  // Resolved at init time per D-64; only languages present in the project are populated.
  bun?: string;       // present whenever anvil itself runs (always)
  node?: string;      // typescript projects
  go?: string;        // golang projects
  python?: string;    // python projects
}

export interface ScaffoldContext {
  projectName: string;
  lang: Lang;
  targetDir: string;
  hasExistingCode: boolean;     // detection result
  skipSeed: boolean;            // authoritative; on re-scaffold loaded from lockfile.context.skipSeed
  sourceDir?: string;
  packageManager?: PackageManager;  // TS/JS only
  defaultBranch: string;        // 'main' default
  nonInteractive: boolean;      // --non-interactive flag only (explicit opt-in; D-67 supersedes D-56)
  toolchain: ToolchainVersions; // resolved at init per D-64; recorded in lockfile
  anvilVersion: string;         // from package.json
}

// ─── Manifest ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
export type FileSource = 'static' | 'template' | 'generator';

export interface ManifestEntry {
  src: string;                  // path within static/<lang>/ (for static/template) or generator id
  dest: string;                 // target path relative to ScaffoldContext.targetDir
  source: FileSource;
  when?: (ctx: ScaffoldContext) => boolean;   // optional include predicate
}

export interface LanguageManifest {
  lang: Lang;
  entries: ManifestEntry[];
}

// ─── FsTree (D-40) ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
export type FsTreeAction = 'create' | 'update' | 'unchanged';

export interface FsTreeEntry {
  path: string;                 // relative to targetDir; posix-normalized
  content: string;              // text only in v1 — no Buffer/binary support
  source: FileSource;
}

export interface FsTreeChange {
  path: string;
  action: FsTreeAction;
}

// ─── Conflict resolution (re-scaffold prompt — interactive only) ─────
export type ConflictAction = 'overwrite' | 'skip' | 'abort';

export interface ConflictResult {
  path: string;
  action: ConflictAction;
}

export type ConflictHandler = (
  path: string,
  existingContent: string,
  newContent: string,
) => Promise<ConflictResult>;

// ─── Conflict reporter (non-interactive — D-67) ──────────────────────
// In --non-interactive mode the engine does NOT call ConflictHandler per file.
// Instead the engine collects all UPDATE entries, hands the changeset to the
// reporter, and exits non-zero with no files written (all-or-nothing).
export interface ConflictReport {
  updates: Array<{ path: string; existingContent: string; newContent: string }>;
  // Reporter renders unified diffs to stderr and is responsible for the exit-1 contract.
}

// ─── Lockfile (.anvil.lock) ──────────────────────────────────────────
export interface LockfileEntry {
  path: string;
  checksum: string;             // 'sha256:<64-hex>'
  source: FileSource;
}

export interface AnvilLockfile {
  version: string;              // anvil version that generated the project
  lang: Lang;
  context: {
    projectName: string;
    packageManager?: PackageManager;
    defaultBranch: string;
    sourceDir?: string;
    skipSeed: boolean;          // authoritative on re-scaffold
  };
  toolchain: ToolchainVersions; // resolved at init per D-64
  files: LockfileEntry[];
  createdAt: string;            // ISO 8601
  updatedAt: string;            // ISO 8601
}
```

**Notes:**
- `ConflictAction` has 3 values, not 4. `'diff'` is an *internal prompt loop state* inside the handler (TIX-000022); it is never a terminal `ConflictResult`.
- `FsTreeEntry.content` is `string` only in v1. We do not scaffold binary files; if that need arises post-v1, extend the type then.
- `skipSeed` is stored on both `ScaffoldContext` and `AnvilLockfile.context`. On re-scaffold the lockfile value is authoritative — do NOT recompute from `hasExistingCode`.
- `nonInteractive` is set ONLY by the explicit `--non-interactive` flag (D-67). TTY-absence does NOT auto-enable it; piping without the flag is a clean error in TIX-000023.
- `toolchain` is resolved at init time per D-64 (latest stable per language) and persisted in the lockfile so re-scaffolds reuse the same versions deterministically.
- Checksums are SHA-256 over the raw bytes written. No CRLF/LF/trailing-newline normalization. (See `specs/cli/scaffold-engine.md` Filesystem Invariants.)

## Reference Implementation

Per D-69, study these projects before coding:

- **`tj/commander.js`** — canonical Node CLI argument parsing. Study how subcommands, options, and `--version` are wired.
- **`vercel/next.js` / `create-next-app`** — reference for the overall CLI shape, headless flag conventions, and how a scaffolder bootstraps without subcommand sprawl.
- **Yeoman generators** (`~/.projects/oss/yeoman-generator`) — long-lived scaffolder; see its CLI bootstrap and `Generator.fs.write` patterns for inspiration on the FsTree-style staging API.
- **Nx tree** — model for FsTree (D-40); virtual filesystem with deferred flush.

### Updates from D-39..D-67 sweep

- The body above already reflects: D-39 (no `update` command in v1), D-44 (shared `src/types.ts`), D-45 (Bun-only distribution), D-56→D-67 (`--non-interactive` is opt-in only), D-64 (toolchain context + lockfile), and D-67 Part B (production deps list). This footer remains as a pointer; the body is the source of truth.

## Purpose

Create the ESLint plugin scaffold that will host all anvil custom lint rules for TypeScript/JS. This is a CommonJS module imported by the project's `eslint.config.mjs` via relative path. No rules are implemented yet — this sets up the harness and test infrastructure.

## Spec References

- `specs/rules/lint-rules.md` — Architecture > Component Overview (file tree under `static/typescript/lint-rules/`)
- `specs/rules/lint-rules.md` — Language-Specific Implementation Notes > TypeScript/JS (CommonJS module, relative import, ESLint v9+ flat config)
- `specs/rules/lint-rules.md` — Key Interfaces > ESLint Rule Module (module.exports shape)
- `specs/rules/lint-rules.md` — Design Decisions: D-15 (ESLint v9+ flat config with local plugin via relative import)
- `specs/rules/lint-rules.md` — Testing Strategy > Per-Rule Unit Tests (RuleTester usage)

## Background

The lint rules are shipped as static files inside anvil's source tree (under `static/typescript/lint-rules/`). When anvil scaffolds a TS project, these files are copied to `tools/lint-rules/` in the target project. The rules run via ESLint v9+ flat config. The plugin is imported in the generated `eslint.config.mjs` like this:

```javascript
import anvilPlugin from './tools/lint-rules/plugin.js';
```

This ticket creates the empty plugin shell and test infrastructure. Subsequent tickets (TIX-000029 through TIX-000032) add the actual rules.

## Files to Create

```
static/typescript/lint-rules/
├── plugin.js              # ESLint plugin entry — exports { rules: {} } object
├── anti-slop/             # Empty directory for anti-slop rules (create with .gitkeep)
├── structural/            # Empty directory for structural rules (create with .gitkeep)
└── test-quality/          # Empty directory for test quality rules (create with .gitkeep)

tests/lint-rules/typescript/
├── helpers.js             # RuleTester setup with TypeScript parser config
└── plugin.test.js         # Verify plugin loads, exports expected shape
```

## Implementation Details

### `static/typescript/lint-rules/plugin.js`

This must be a **CommonJS module** (not ESM) — ESLint plugins use `module.exports`:

```javascript
// CommonJS module — ESLint plugins must use module.exports
const rules = {};
// Rules will be added by subsequent tickets (TIX-000029 through TIX-000032)

const plugin = {
  rules,
  configs: {},
};

// Build the recommended config after the plugin object exists
// (the config references the plugin itself)
plugin.configs.recommended = {
  plugins: { anvil: plugin },
  rules: {},  // Will be populated as rules are added
};

module.exports = plugin;
```

Note: The `configs.recommended` must reference the plugin object itself (for ESLint v9 flat config self-referencing pattern). Build the config after the plugin object is created, not inline.

### `tests/lint-rules/typescript/helpers.js`

Create a RuleTester configured for TypeScript parsing. This helper is imported by all rule test files in subsequent tickets.

```javascript
const { RuleTester } = require('eslint');

const ruleTester = new RuleTester({
  languageOptions: {
    parser: require('@typescript-eslint/parser'),
    parserOptions: {
      ecmaVersion: 2022,
      sourceType: 'module',
    },
  },
});

module.exports = { ruleTester };
```

Key points:
- Use `languageOptions.parser` (ESLint v9 flat config format), not the legacy `parser` key.
- Use `@typescript-eslint/parser` — this must be installed as a devDependency in anvil's `package.json`.
- Export the configured `ruleTester` instance for reuse by all test files.

### `tests/lint-rules/typescript/plugin.test.js`

```javascript
const { describe, it, expect } = require('vitest');  // or use vitest globals if configured
const plugin = require('../../../static/typescript/lint-rules/plugin.js');

describe('anvil ESLint plugin', () => {
  it('loads without error', () => {
    expect(plugin).toBeDefined();
  });

  it('exports a rules object', () => {
    expect(plugin.rules).toBeDefined();
    expect(typeof plugin.rules).toBe('object');
  });

  it('exports a configs object with recommended', () => {
    expect(plugin.configs).toBeDefined();
    expect(plugin.configs.recommended).toBeDefined();
  });

  it('recommended config references the plugin', () => {
    expect(plugin.configs.recommended.plugins).toBeDefined();
    expect(plugin.configs.recommended.plugins.anvil).toBe(plugin);
  });

  it('recommended config has a rules object', () => {
    expect(plugin.configs.recommended.rules).toBeDefined();
    expect(typeof plugin.configs.recommended.rules).toBe('object');
  });
});
```

## Dependencies to Install

Ensure these are in anvil's `package.json` `devDependencies` (add if not already present):
- `eslint` (v9+)
- `@typescript-eslint/parser`
- `@typescript-eslint/eslint-plugin`

Run `bun install` after adding any new dependencies.

## Tests

Run with: `bun test tests/lint-rules/typescript/plugin.test.js`

Verify:
1. Plugin loads without error
2. `exports.rules` is an object (empty at this point)
3. `exports.configs.recommended` exists
4. `exports.configs.recommended.plugins.anvil` references the plugin itself
5. `exports.configs.recommended.rules` is an object

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `static/typescript/lint-rules/plugin.js` exists and is a valid CommonJS module
- [ ] `static/typescript/lint-rules/anti-slop/`, `structural/`, `test-quality/` directories exist
- [ ] `tests/lint-rules/typescript/helpers.js` exports a configured `ruleTester`
- [ ] `tests/lint-rules/typescript/plugin.test.js` passes all assertions
- [ ] Plugin self-references correctly in `configs.recommended.plugins.anvil`
- [ ] `bun test tests/lint-rules/typescript/plugin.test.js` passes

### Updates from D-39..D-61 sweep

- **Add `error-handling/` directory** alongside `anti-slop/`, `structural/`,
  `test-quality/` to host RULE-09 `no-silent-error-swallow` (D-50). Plugin
  scaffold should expect this fourth category.
- **No `eslint-plugin-barrel-files` dependency** (D-57). Do not add it to the
  plugin's peer-deps or recommend it in the harness.

## Reference Projects

- **Factory AI `eslint-plugin`** (`~/.projects/oss/eslint-plugin`) — battle-tested local ESLint plugin design pattern that anvil's plugin scaffold mirrors. See its `index.js` plugin module shape and rule organization (`rules/<category>/<rule>.js`).

## Purpose

Implement the first batch of anti-slop ESLint rules focused on catch/error block analysis and regex-based comment detection. These are custom ESLint rules that detect coding agent laziness patterns.

## Spec References

- `specs/rules/lint-rules.md` — Rule Catalog > Category A: Anti-Slop Rules (RULE-01, RULE-02, RULE-03, RULE-05)
- `specs/rules/lint-rules.md` — Key Interfaces > ESLint Rule Module (module.exports shape with meta + create)
- `specs/rules/lint-rules.md` — Language-Specific Implementation Notes > TypeScript/JS (CatchClause, context.filename)
- `specs/rules/lint-rules.md` — Testing Strategy > Per-Rule Unit Tests (RuleTester, 3+ valid, 3+ invalid cases)
- `specs/rules/lint-rules.md` — Design Decisions: D-15 (ESLint v9+ flat config with local plugin)

## Background

These rules are CommonJS modules that live in `static/typescript/lint-rules/anti-slop/`. They are part of the anvil ESLint plugin created in TIX-000028. When anvil scaffolds a TS project, these files are copied to `tools/lint-rules/anti-slop/` in the target project.

Each rule module must follow the ESLint rule shape:
```javascript
module.exports = {
  meta: {
    type: 'problem',
    docs: { description: '...', recommended: true },
    messages: { messageId: 'Error message' },
    schema: [],
  },
  create(context) {
    return {
      // AST visitor methods
    };
  },
};
```

## Files to Create

```
static/typescript/lint-rules/anti-slop/
├── no-log-and-continue.js
├── no-error-obscuring.js
├── no-placeholder-comments.js
└── no-log-and-throw.js

tests/lint-rules/typescript/anti-slop/
├── no-log-and-continue.test.js
├── no-error-obscuring.test.js
├── no-placeholder-comments.test.js
└── no-log-and-throw.test.js
```

## File to Update

- `static/typescript/lint-rules/plugin.js` — import and register all 4 rules in the `rules` object and add them to `configs.recommended.rules`.

## Rule Implementations

### RULE-01: `no-log-and-continue` (`static/typescript/lint-rules/anti-slop/no-log-and-continue.js`)

**What it detects**: catch blocks that only log the error without handling it (no re-throw, no return, no recovery logic).

**AST approach**:
- Visit `CatchClause` nodes
- Examine the body's statements
- Check if the body contains ONLY call expressions to logging functions (`console.log`, `console.error`, `console.warn`, `console.info`, `console.debug`, or `logger.*` / `log.*` member expressions)
- If the body has no `ThrowStatement`, no `ReturnStatement`, and no other statements besides log calls, report the node

**Logging function detection**: A call expression is a logging call if:
- It's `console.log`, `console.error`, `console.warn`, `console.info`, `console.debug` (MemberExpression where object is `console`)
- It's a member expression call on an object named `logger` or `log` (e.g., `logger.error(...)`, `log.warn(...)`)

**Message ID**: `logAndContinue`
**Message**: `"Catch block only logs the error without handling it. Re-throw, return an error, or add recovery logic."`

**Valid cases (should NOT flag)**:
```javascript
// Re-throws after logging
try { foo(); } catch (e) { console.error(e); throw e; }

// Returns after logging
try { foo(); } catch (e) { console.error(e); return null; }

// Has recovery logic beyond just logging
try { foo(); } catch (e) { console.error(e); fallback(); }

// Empty catch (different anti-pattern, not this rule)
try { foo(); } catch (e) { }

// Only a throw (no logging)
try { foo(); } catch (e) { throw new AppError(e); }
```

**Invalid cases (should flag)**:
```javascript
// Only logs
try { foo(); } catch (e) { console.error(e); }

// Only logs with console.log
try { foo(); } catch (e) { console.log("error", e); }

// Only logs with a logger
try { foo(); } catch (e) { logger.error("failed", e); }

// Multiple log calls but nothing else
try { foo(); } catch (e) { console.error(e); console.log("details"); }
```

### RULE-02: `no-error-obscuring` (`static/typescript/lint-rules/anti-slop/no-error-obscuring.js`)

**What it detects**: catch blocks that discard the original error context by returning a default value or throwing a generic error without wrapping the caught error.

**AST approach**:
- Visit `CatchClause` nodes. Get the caught error parameter name (e.g., `e` from `catch (e)`).
- **Check 1 — Default return**: Look for `ReturnStatement` whose argument is a literal value (`null`, `undefined`, `false`, `0`, `""`, `[]`, `{}`) or identifier (`undefined`) and the catch body does NOT reference the caught error parameter in any meaningful way (no re-throw, no wrapping).
- **Check 2 — Generic throw**: Look for `ThrowStatement` containing `new Error("string literal")` where the `Error` constructor's argument does NOT reference the caught error parameter. For example, `throw new Error("Something went wrong")` discards the original error, but `throw new Error("Failed", { cause: e })` or `throw new AppError(e.message)` preserves it.

**How to check if caught error is referenced**: Walk the throw/return expression AST subtree and check if any `Identifier` node matches the catch parameter name.

**Message IDs**: `defaultReturn`, `genericThrow`
**Messages**:
- `defaultReturn`: `"Error context is discarded by returning a default value. Wrap the original error or propagate it."`
- `genericThrow`: `"Error context is discarded by throwing a generic error. Wrap the original error with { cause: <error> } or use a custom error type."`

**Valid cases**:
```javascript
// Re-throws original error
try { foo(); } catch (e) { throw e; }

// Wraps with cause
try { foo(); } catch (e) { throw new Error("failed", { cause: e }); }

// Returns after referencing the error
try { foo(); } catch (e) { return { error: e.message }; }

// Custom error wrapping
try { foo(); } catch (e) { throw new AppError("context", e); }
```

**Invalid cases**:
```javascript
// Returns a default, ignoring the error
try { foo(); } catch (e) { return null; }

// Returns empty array, ignoring error
try { foo(); } catch (e) { return []; }

// Throws generic error without wrapping
try { foo(); } catch (e) { throw new Error("Something went wrong"); }

// Returns false without using error
try { foo(); } catch (e) { return false; }
```

### RULE-03: `no-placeholder-comments` (`static/typescript/lint-rules/anti-slop/no-placeholder-comments.js`)

**What it detects**: Lazy placeholder comments that signal unfinished work without actionable context.

**Implementation approach**: This rule does NOT use AST visitors. Instead, use the `Program` visitor to iterate over all comments via `context.sourceCode.getAllComments()`.

**Patterns to flag** (case-insensitive regex matching on comment text):
1. `TODO`/`FIXME`/`HACK` without a ticket reference: `/\b(TODO|FIXME|HACK)\b(?!.*\b[A-Z]+-\d+)/i` — flags "TODO: fix this" but allows "TODO(JIRA-123): fix this"
2. Lazy deferral: `/\bimplement(ed)?\s+(this\s+)?later\b/i`
3. Vague future work: `/\badd\s+.*(error|logging|validation|tests?|handling)\b/i`
4. Placeholder signals: `/\bplaceholder\b/i`
5. Fill-in signals: `/\bfill\s+(this\s+)?in\b/i`
6. Temporary markers: `/\btemporary\b/i` (but NOT inside longer words)

**Message ID**: `placeholderComment`
**Message**: `"Placeholder comment detected. Either implement the TODO or remove it."`

Report on each matching comment node.

**Valid cases** (should NOT flag):
```javascript
// TODO with ticket reference
// TODO(PROJ-123): Optimize query performance

// Descriptive comment, not a placeholder
// This function handles user authentication

// FIXME with ticket ref
// FIXME GH-456: Race condition in cache invalidation
```

**Invalid cases** (should flag):
```javascript
// TODO: fix this later
// implement later
// add error handling
// placeholder
// fill in the logic
// temporary workaround
// HACK: quick fix
```

### RULE-05: `no-log-and-throw` (`static/typescript/lint-rules/anti-slop/no-log-and-throw.js`)

**What it detects**: Logging and throwing in the same block — this creates duplicate error reports because the caller will also handle the error.

**AST approach**:
- Visit `CatchClause` nodes (primary target)
- Also visit `BlockStatement` nodes to catch non-catch blocks with the same pattern
- For each block, check if it contains BOTH:
  1. A logging call (same detection as RULE-01: `console.*`, `logger.*`, `log.*`)
  2. A `ThrowStatement`
- If both are present, report on the **log call** (the throw is the correct behavior; the log is redundant)

**Message ID**: `logAndThrow`
**Message**: `"Logging and throwing in the same block creates duplicate error reports. Choose one."`

**Valid cases**:
```javascript
// Only throws (correct)
try { foo(); } catch (e) { throw new AppError(e); }

// Only logs with return (acceptable — handled by RULE-01 if no recovery)
try { foo(); } catch (e) { console.error(e); return null; }

// Logs in one block, throws in another (different scopes)
if (condition) { console.error("bad"); } else { throw new Error("fail"); }
```

**Invalid cases**:
```javascript
// Log + throw in catch block
try { foo(); } catch (e) { console.error(e); throw e; }

// Log + throw in catch with logger
try { foo(); } catch (e) { logger.error("failed", e); throw new AppError(e); }

// Log + throw in a regular block
{ console.log("about to fail"); throw new Error("fail"); }
```

## Updating plugin.js

After creating all 4 rule files, update `static/typescript/lint-rules/plugin.js` to import and register them:

```javascript
const noLogAndContinue = require('./anti-slop/no-log-and-continue.js');
const noErrorObscuring = require('./anti-slop/no-error-obscuring.js');
const noPlaceholderComments = require('./anti-slop/no-placeholder-comments.js');
